<HEADLINE>
<P>
FIGURE IN HASTINGS CASE ORDERED JAILED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A federal judge on Tuesday found disbarred attorney William Borders in contempt 
of court and ordered him to jail for refusing to answer questions from a Senate 
panel gathering evidence in the Alcee L. Hastings impeachment trial. U.S. 
District Judge Thomas Pennfield Jackson gave Borders until 10 a.m. Friday to 
surrender to federal marshals. 
</P>
<P>
The committee is collecting evidence concerning charges that Hastings conspired 
with Borders to obtain a $150,000 payoff and lied about it before a jury that 
acquitted him in 1983. Borders was convicted in 1982, disbarred and sent to 
prison for 33 months. 
</P>
<P>
Hastings, who was impeached by the House in August, 1988, is also accused of 
improperly disclosing information that government investigators obtained 
through a court-approved wiretap. 
</P>
<P>
Once the committee finishes its report, the full Senate will vote on whether to 
remove Hastings from the federal bench and thus take away the $89,500 annual 
salary he continues to receive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
