<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: ANAHEIM; 
</P>
<P>
BUDDY EBSEN BECOMES AN HONORARY CITIZEN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Actor Buddy Ebsen became an honorary citizen of Anaheim and Orange County at 
Wednesday's Anaheim City Council meeting, and he jokingly declared that the 
certificate "will allow me to get parking tickets fixed in Orange County." 
</P>
<P>
Anaheim Mayor Fred Hunter and Supervisor Don R. Roth, whose district includes 
Anaheim, presented Ebsen with the awards in honor of his 60 years as an actor, 
dancer and songwriter. 
</P>
<P>
"This is overwhelming," said Ebsen, who is perhaps best-known for his role as 
Jed Clampett on the television comedy "The Beverly Hillbillies." 
</P>
<P>
"I never expected to get any kind of award for having a lifetime of fun," Ebsen 
said. 
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Ebsen's footprints and handprints were embedded in cement 
at Movieland Wax Museum in Buena Park. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Buddy Ebsen's fresh imprints, above, at Movieland Wax Museum in Buena 
Park. Ebsen then happily washes his hands of the affair in his honor. DON 
KELSEN / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
