<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE SIDELINES; 
</P>
<P>
CAN'T HOST SOCCER GAME, CHILE TOLD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
ZURICH, Switzerland 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FIFA, world soccer's ruling body, rejected an appeal today by Chile to let it 
host a crucial World Cup qualifying match against Venezuela and ruled the match 
should be played in Argentina. A FIFA communique said the match on Sunday will 
take place in Mendoza. 
</P>
<P>
Chile's soccer association appealed to FIFA on Tuesday to overturn its ban on 
the country hosting the Venezuela match. 
</P>
<P>
FIFA imposed the suspension last Friday as one of a number of sanctions 
following disturbances at the Aug. 13 match between Chile and Brazil at the 
capital's stadium. The FIFA communique said charges against the Chilean 
association included poor organization of the game, during which home fans 
threw objects at the visiting team, the referee and linesmen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
